<h1>The Spacefarer's paradox</h1>

<p>The <i>spacefarer's paradox</i> is based on the possibility that if we continue to improve our technology, it's likely that for a distant enough target, <b>a spacecraft launched in the future might actually arrive before a spacecraft launched right now</b>. Put another way, if we continue to improve our technology, the benefit of waiting may outweigh the benefit of launching earlier.</p>

<p>Even given the spacefarer's paradox, there's a point at which the benefit of waiting no longer outweighs the benefit of launching earlier. If a decade of research results in us developing a spacecraft that can arrive only two years faster than the previous model, then the benefit of waiting no longer outweighs the benefit of launching earlier. This is demonstrated in the following simulation:</p>

